menu "merge_wire UART <-> RS485 bridge"

    config MERGE_WIRE_ISR_IN_IRAM
        bool "Place bridge ISRs and buffers in IRAM/internal RAM"
        default y
        help
            Keeps the bridge interrupt handlers executable and their data
            reachable while the flash cache is disabled (flash writes, OTA).
            Also adds ESP_INTR_FLAG_IRAM to both interrupt allocations.
            Disable only if IRAM is scarce and no flash operations run
            while the bridge is active.


    choice MERGE_WIRE_COLLISION_POLICY
        prompt "Collision handling for the chunk on the wire"
        default MERGE_WIRE_COLLISION_RETRY
        help
            What to do with the MAIN -> RS485 chunk that was being
            transmitted when a collision was detected.

        config MERGE_WIRE_COLLISION_RETRY
            bool "Replay the chunk (commit only when verified)"
            help
                The in-flight chunk is only returned to the ring buffer once
                TX_DONE confirms it reached the wire without a clash. On a
                collision it is rewound and replayed after a randomized
                exponential backoff, up to MW_MAX_RETRIES attempts, then
                dropped. This behaves like a native CSMA node when chunks
                align with the sender's frames (idle-gap delimited traffic).

        config MERGE_WIRE_COLLISION_DROP
            bool "Drop the chunk (back off, continue with next data)"
            help
                The bridge is frame-unaware: every receiver already saw the
                corrupted frame, so replaying a possibly mid-frame slice
                cannot repair it and may inject a duplicated garbled
                fragment. This policy drops the collided chunk immediately,
                backs off with jitter to avoid re-colliding in lockstep, and
                continues with whatever is queued next, leaving recovery to
                the end-to-end protocol. MW_MAX_RETRIES has no effect.
    endchoice

endmenu
